The importance ol salt in the economy os medieval lile was very great. From November to May,the mass ol the English people lived on salted provisions. On every fast day salted fish was the customary diet ol those who had anything more than bread to eat. The trade in salted

’ fish was a very important and lucrative employment. It was the princi·

pal means ol preserving lood in winter, and was the first condiment at all times. It was in the period 1 write about entirely derived from solar evaporation. A wet summer raised the price of salt sar more than it did that ol wheat, and in ordinary times the price of salt away srom the sea closely corresponds, the above exception taken, to the price of wheat. It could be procured abundantly and cheaply from the salterns of Westem France. Long alter the severance of Guienne from England was an accomplished fact, English monarchs, in their treaties with France, demanded the free export ol Gascon salt as a condition ol their negotiations.
